# System Baseline v1

## Objective
Build a 2–3 node LoRa GNSS system:
- Raspberry Pi 4 = gateway
- Raspberry Pi Pico 2W = end nodes
- each node reads local GNSS
- each node transmits compact LoRa packets
- gateway receives packets and stores latest state per node
- gateway later serves an offline map UI

## Toolchain
### Node side
- Arduino IDE
- Arduino-Pico core
- RadioLib
- TinyGPSPlus

### Gateway side
- Raspberry Pi OS
- C in terminal
- spidev for SPI
- libgpiod for GPIO

## Initial topology
- point-to-point uplink only
- no mesh
- no relay
- no ACK yet
- final target supports 2–3 nodes

## Node IDs
- node 1
- node 2
- node 3

## First packet format
[node_id:1][seq:1][timestamp:4][lat_i32:4][lon_i32:4][alt_i16:2][sats:1][fix:1][reserved:1]

Total: 18 bytes

## Coordinate encoding
lat_i32 = latitude * 1e7
lon_i32 = longitude * 1e7

## First radio-mode goal
- same frequency on all devices
- same BW/SF/CR on all devices
- one-way uplink only
- staggered transmissions later for multi-node operation

## First milestone
One Pico node sends one valid fixed-format packet.
Pi 4 receives and decodes it correctly.
